sed_bytes\": 70320, \"delta_hit\": 4249, \"delta_miss\": 1, \"delta_total\": 4250, \"delta_miss_rate\": 0.000235, \"cache_used_post_pct_of_limit\": 0.033531},\n    {\"worker_idx\": 5, \"pre_hit\": 27, \"pre_miss\": 17, \"pre_used_bytes\": 65968, \"post_hit\": 4246, \"post_miss\": 18, \"post_used_bytes\": 70320, \"delta_hit\": 4219, \"delta_miss\": 1, \"delta_total\": 4220, \"delta_miss_rate\": 0.000237, \"cache_used_post_pct_of_limit\": 0.033531},\n    {\"worker_idx\": 6, \"pre_hit\": 27, \"pre_miss\": 17, \"pre_used_bytes\": 65968, \"post_hit\": 4346, \"post_miss\": 18, \"post_used_bytes\": 70320, \"delta_hit\": 4319, \"delta_miss\": 1, \"delta_total\": 4320, \"delta_miss_rate\": 0.000231, \"cache_used_post_pct_of_limit\": 0.033531},\n    {\"worker_idx\": 7, \"pre_hit\": 27, \"pre_miss\": 17, \"pre_used_bytes\": 65968, \"post_hit\": 4346, \"post_miss\": 18, \"post_used_bytes\": 70320, \"delta_hit\": 4319, \"delta_miss\": 1, \"delta_total\": 4320, \"delta_miss_rate\": 0.000231, \"cache_used_post_pct_of_limit\": 0.033531}\n  ],\n  \"aggregate_summary\": {\n    \"delta_miss_rate_min\": 0.000230,\n    \"delta_miss_rate_median\": 0.0002315,\n    \"delta_miss_rate_max\": 0.000237,\n    \"delta_miss_rate_stddev\": 0.00000234,\n    \"cache_used_pct_min\": 0.033531,\n    \"cache_used_pct_median\": 0.033531,\n    \"cache_used_pct_max\": 0.033531,\n    \"cache_used_pct_stddev\": 0.0\n  },\n  \"decision_matrix_evaluation\": \"Row 1 (SKIP_G4) matches: all 8 workers have cache_used_post_pct_of_limit = 0.033531 (3.35%) which is < 50%, AND all 8 workers have delta_miss_rate in [0.0230%, 0.0237%] which is < 5%. Row 2 (FULL_G4_SWEEP) does not match: no worker hits >= 90% cache used or > 15% miss rate; not even close. Row 3 (DISPATCH_BIAS_FLAG) does not match — see `dispatch_bias_evidence` below: max/min ratio for delta_hit is 1.032x (4354 / 4219) < 2x; delta_miss is uniformly 1 across workers; cache_used_post_bytes is uniformly 70320 across workers. Verdict: SKIP_G4, no bias flag.\",\n  \"dispatch_bias_evidence\": {\n    \"checked\": true,\n    \"delta_hit_min_max\": [4219, 4354],\n    \"delta_hit_max_over_min_ratio\": 1.0320,\n    \"delta_miss_min_max\": [1, 1],\n    \"delta_miss_max_over_min_ratio\": 1.0,\n    \"post_used_bytes_min_max\": [70320, 70320],\n    \"post_used_bytes_max_over_min_ratio\": 1.0,\n    \"verdict\": \"round-robin dispatch is uniform within ~3.2% across workers on this AC-020 concurrent body; well under the 2x bias threshold. Page-cache footprint is bit-identical across workers (every reader sees the same query mix and the fixture is small).\"\n  },\n  \"ac017_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"release\",\n      \"notes\": \"`cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`. `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok`. Total wall: 14.70 s for the perf_gates test binary.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac018_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"drain_ms\": 80,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"release profile; `AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=80`. Well under the 2 s gate. Slightly faster than G.1's 95 ms; consistent with run-to-run host jitter on this Linux 5.15-tegra worktree.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"g3_5_diagnostic_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"profile\": \"dev (debug_assertions=true)\",\n      \"command\": \"G3_5_OUTPUT_PATH=/tmp/g3_5_evidence.json cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- --ignored g3_5_cache_pressure_telemetry --nocapture\",\n      \"concurrent_ms\": 196,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"Test is `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`-gated because the underlying `cache_status_per_worker_for_test` accessor follows the F.0 / G.1 `#[cfg(debug_assertions)] #[doc(hidden)]` convention. Spec §4.4 suggested `cargo test --release`, but that compiles out the helper; G.1's reader_pool tests ran in dev mode for the same reason. AC-017 / AC-018 still ran in release per §4.3.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n    \"Per-worker page-cache footprint is BIT-IDENTICAL across all 8 workers post-AC020 (70320 bytes each). This is a fingerprint of the small AC-020 fixture: 4 seeded docs + 4 distinct queries means each thread-affine connection materializes the exact same set of b-tree / vec0 / fts5 pages into its private page cache. On a larger fixture this uniformity would relax. For the G.3.5 SKIP_G4 verdict it tightens the case: there is no worker outlier hiding behind the median.\",\n    \"Hit:miss ratio is ~4300:1 on the concurrent body — the F.0 reader page caches are running in steady-state happy-path mode after the 16-search warmup. The single residual miss per worker per concurrent body is plausibly the first vec0/fts5 page that escapes the warmup query set. In other words the residual AC-020 gap on this host is NOT a page-cache-thrashing problem; it is something else (most likely the SQLite pcache1 global mutex itself, the WAL shared-memory atomics, or the parse_compile floor — all already on the orchestrator's G-phase candidate list).\",\n    \"delta_used_bytes (post - pre) is +4352 bytes uniformly per worker. That is exactly +1 SQLite default page (4 KiB) plus a small per-connection bookkeeping delta. A second page would only be materialized under cache pressure. The 2 MiB per-connection cache is thus carrying the AC-020 working set with ~30x headroom on this fixture.\",\n    \"Because cache_size is the canonical SQLite default (-2000 KiB), the 50% / 90% thresholds in §2 are evaluated against 2 MiB. If the orchestrator wants to verify the assumption empirically rather than assume it, a one-line `PRAGMA cache_size` readback in the same broadcast would suffice; G.3.5 deliberately did not add that to keep the diff minimal and inside the 'measure-only' mandate.\"\n  ],\n  \"data_for_pivot\": {\n    \"if_skip_g4\": {\n      \"next_action\": \"Defer G.4 entirely on this fixture and host. The page-cache evidence does not justify the run cost. Reassess G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) per Pack 6.G handoff §4 default ordering — parse_compile = 22.52% conc from G.0 telemetry is the next-highest-share canonical-SQLite-amenable residual. If G.2 also lands INCONCLUSIVE / KEEP-but-no-AC-020-closure, the §9 packet-close path applies: ship 0.6.0 with REQ-020 deferred, open Pack 7 with the cumulative G-phase evidence including G.3.5's SKIP_G4 verdict as the bound on per-connection page-cache contribution.\",\n      \"rationale\": \"Both SKIP thresholds are met by ~15x margin (3.35% vs 50% used; 0.023% vs 5% miss). A bigger reader cache cannot help when the existing one has 96.65% headroom and the steady-state miss rate is 1 page per 4300 hits.\",\n      \"rejected_alternative_PROBE_G4_MINUS_8000\": \"Not selected. PROBE would be defensible if any worker were near a 50% cache_used or 5% miss-rate threshold; none are. Spending the worktree-spawn cost on a single sweep point that the data already says will be flat is not a positive-EV step.\"\n    },\n    \"if_full_g4_sweep\": {\n      \"next_action\": \"Not applicable to this evidence. Recorded for completeness: would have spawned G.4 with the full {-2000, -8000, -32000} KiB grid.\"\n    },\n    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer optional per Pack 6.G §7 (G.3.5 is a screening pass, not a KEEP/REVERT lever — it adds debug-only diagnostic plumbing and a single `#[ignore]`-gated test). If the orchestrator wants reviewer cover anyway, the diff is small and the SKIP_G4 verdict is supported entirely by the 8 numbers in `per_worker_telemetry`.\"\n  },\n  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"`./scripts/agent-verify.sh` (verbose) returned `ok verify 71s`. Steps: lint-rust 317ms, lint-rustfmt 208ms, lint-migrations 54ms, lint-python 21ms, lint-md-links 64ms, typecheck-rust 229ms, typecheck-python 1889ms, test-rust 67468ms, test-python 869ms. ESLint / TS / markdownlint / prettier are environment skips, not failures. `cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings` ran clean (one pre-existing dead_code warning on `ReaderWorkerPool::worker_count` / `live_count` was already present on the G.3.5 prompt tip d9adf23 and is unrelated to this commit; verified by `git stash && cargo build --release` on the unmodified tree).\",\n  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\", \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.3.5 only adds `sqlite3_db_status` (per-connection counter read) FFI calls. No `sqlite3_config` (capital-C global) calls were added or modified. Diff: `git show b8a3770 -- src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs` shows only a new `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` ReaderRequest variant + helper struct + worker arm + read_cache_status fn.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\", \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs / Cargo.toml feature changes. Canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\", \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared-statement cache) is still future-packet.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\", \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size or mmap_size production-default changes — G.3.5 explicitly measures only. `cache_size_limit_bytes_assumed` is the SQLite-default 2 MiB; nothing in `Engine::open_with_embedder_for_test` reader-open path has been touched.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\", \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader open flags untouched: still `Connection::open(&path)` with default flags. `sqlite3_db_status` is a per-connection counter read; not an open-flag change.\"}\n  ],\n  \"tests_run\": [\n    \"cargo build -p fathomdb-engine --tests — green\",\n    \"cargo build --release -p fathomdb-engine — green (pre-existing dead_code warning on worker_count/live_count, unrelated)\",\n    \"cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test reader_pool — 6 tests green (4 F.0 worker-pool tests + 2 G.1 lookaside tests)\",\n    \"G3_5_OUTPUT_PATH=/tmp/g3_5_evidence.json cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- --ignored g3_5_cache_pressure_telemetry --nocapture — 1 passed, sidecar JSON written\",\n    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture — 2 passed; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=80\",\n    \"cargo fmt --all -- --check — clean (after one fmt run on the new test body)\",\n    \"cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings — clean\",\n    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — rc=0, 71s wall\"\n  ],\n  \"next_phase_input\": {\n    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Apply the §8 stop rule SKIP_G4 branch: defer G.4 (per-worker reader PRAGMA cache_size sweep) and reassess G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) per Pack 6.G handoff §4 default ordering. The G.3.5 evidence bounds the per-connection page-cache contribution to AC-020 at <= ~0.023% miss / <= 3.35% used — i.e. there is essentially no headroom for a bigger reader cache to recover. The remaining canonical-SQLite levers worth a worktree spawn are G.2 (parse_compile floor, 22.52% conc share from G.0) and / or G.3 (WAL checkpoint policy, only if G.0 evidence supports a write-side residual; G.0 reported checkpoint cost is small on the read-heavy fixture).\",\n    \"for_packet_close\": \"G.3.5 itself is a screening step; it does not move AC-020 numbers. Cumulative-vs-F.0 speedup is unchanged from the G.1 INCONCLUSIVE state (~3.53x median on this host vs the 5.33x KEEP target). Per Pack 6.G §9, packet success is 'every canonical-SQLite lever tried, KEEPs landed, residual gap documented for Pack 7' — G.3.5 contributes the page-cache leg of that documentation by ruling out the per-connection cache_size lever as a closer.\"\n  }\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":